esidents, a trend that accelerated after the storm. The market-centered nature of the reforms have ensured that they largely benefited city and regional elites while not significantly aiding the city’s working-class and impoverished populations. Thus reform has come at a cost and that cost, in the long term, could undermine the political gains of the post-Katrina era.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aHurricane Katrina, 2005xPolitical aspects. 0aPolitical culturezLouisianazNew Orleans. 4aU.S. History. 4aUrban Studies.  aNew Orleans, New Orleans in 2005, Katrina, disasters, post-Katrina era, stagnation, urban governance, urban sociology, post-disaster recovery, urban renewal, political arrangement, policy agenda fidelity.1 aThomas, Matthew O., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066749340uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170094140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501700941423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501700941/original  a978-3-11-066749-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles